 Here is a JavaScript function that uses regex to extract a three character code from a filename in the specified format:

```javascript
function extractCodeFromFilename(filename) {
    var match = filename.match(/^([^\.-]+)-(\w{3}).*$/);

    if (match && match[2]) {
        return match[2];
    } else {
        throw new Error("Invalid file name");
    }
}
```
This function first matches the filename parts according to the format using a regex pattern. The pattern `/^([^\.-]+)-(\w{3}).*$/` means: 
- Start of string (^).
- Matches characters that are not dot or dash until you find a dash (-).
- Captures three word character (letters, numbers, underscores) in a group and stores it as the second match.
- Dot (* indicates zero or more occurrences of anything but newline.)
- End of string ($). 

Then if there is a third match which is our code we return that otherwise throw an error.
